07038nam a22008175i 9780822381044DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20012001ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1229160910  a97808223810447 a10.1515/97808223810442doi  a(DE-B1597)552770  a(OCoLC)1167188555  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aE184.A1bM2627 2001 7aSOC0080002bisacsh04a305.8/03407322104aThe Making and Unmaking of Whiteness /ced. by Irene J. Nexica, Eric Klinenberg, Birgit Brander Rasmussen, Matt Wray. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2001] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (352 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tUniversal Freckle, or How I Learned to Be White -- t‘‘The Souls of White Folks’’ -- tThe Mirage of an Unmarked Whiteness -- tWhite Racial Projects -- tThe ‘‘Morphing’’ Properties of Whiteness -- t‘‘White Devils’’ Talk Back: What Antiracists Can Learn from Whites in Detroit -- tTransnational Configurations of Desire: The Nation and its White Closets -- tPerfidious Albion: Whiteness and the International Imagination -- tThe New Liberalism in America: Identity Politics in the ‘‘Vital Center’’ -- tHow Gay Stays White and What Kind of White It Stays -- t(E)racism: Emerging Practices of Antiracist Organizations -- tMoving from Guilt to Action: Antiracist Organizing and the Concept of ‘‘Whiteness’’ for Activism and the Academy -- tBibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBringing together new articles and essays from the controversial Berkeley conference of the same name, The Making and Unmaking of Whiteness presents a fascinating range of inquiry into the nature of whiteness. Representing academics, independent scholars, community organizers, and antiracist activists, the contributors are all leaders in the “second wave” of whiteness studies who collectively aim to combat the historical legacies of white supremacy and to inform those who seek to understand the changing nature of white identity, both in the United States and abroad.With essays devoted to theories of racial domination, comparative global racisms, and transnational white identity, the geographical reach of the volume is significant and broad. Dalton Conley writes on “How I Learned to Be White.” Allan Bérubé discusses the intersection of gay identity and whiteness, and Mab Segrest describes the spiritual price white people pay for living in a system of white supremacy. Other pieces examine the utility of whiteness as a critical term for social analysis and contextualize different attempts at antiracist activism. In a razor-sharp introduction, the editors not only raise provocative questions about the intellectual, social, and political goals of those interested in the study of whiteness but assess several of the topic’s major recurrent themes: the visibility of whiteness (or the lack thereof); the “emptiness” of whiteness as a category of identification; and conceptions of whiteness as a structural privilege, a harbinger of violence, or an institutionalization of European imperialism.Contributors. William Aal, Allan Bérubé, Birgit Brander Rasmussen, Dalton Conley, Troy Duster, Ruth Frankenberg, John Hartigan Jr., Eric Klinenberg, Eric Lott, Irene J. Nexica, Michael Omi, Jasbir Kaur Puar, Mab Segrest, Vron Ware, Howard Winant, Matt Wray  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aRace awarenesszUnited StatesvCongresses. 0aRacismzUnited StatesvCongresses. 0aSocial classeszUnited StatesvCongresses. 0aWhite peoplexRace identityzUnited StatesvCongresses. 0aWhitesxRace identityzUnited StatesvCongresses. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / General